<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-234-135 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 358 344</DOCID><JOURNAL>Technology andamp; Learning  Feb 1991 v11 n5 pA-10(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Lights, cameras, action! (Hill Vocational Center's student-runweekly newscast)(includes related article on Hill Vocational'sacquisition of a Commodore Amiga 2000) (The Commodore Amiga andthe Creative Classroom supplement)andM;</TITLE><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Hill Vocational Center of Lansing, MI, facilitates Station WHBS, astudent-run television newscast created with the resources of aradio station, a remote camera and a Commodore Amigamicrocomputer.andP;  The 30-minute program, which is broadcast over alocal cable channel to more than 40,000 paying subscribers,includes interviews, weather reports and commercials.andP;  TeacherJoanne Mahoney rotates the various positions required to puttogether one newscast per week so that every student has theopportunity to be leader/producer.andP;  Crew assignments range fromfield reporters, anchor people and technical staff.andP;  Students usethe Commodore Amiga 2000 to type up interview questions and tocreate special effects.andP;  Material for the show is stored on disksuntil the master tape is created.andP;  The master tape contains datafrom any of eight different sources including the computer.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Commodore Corp. (Marketing).andO;Product:   Commodore Amiga 2000 (Microcomputer) (Educational use).andO;Topic:     EducationComputer-Assisted InstructionCurriculumSecondary SchoolsBroadcastingPromotion of ProductMarketing Strategy.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>